Today, US graduates are struggling to find a job:

The unemployment rate among new college graduates has averaged 6.6% over the last 12 months,

the highest in a decade, outside of 2020. The jobless rate for people aged 20 to 24 who are look-

ing for work and have at least a bachelor’s degree has risen by ~1.3 percentage points in 3 years.

Two factors come into play here, the softening economy and the emergence of Al. We'll discuss

more about Al in a moment.

Recent statistics show, the unemployment among college grads aged 22 to 27 averaged 5.8% in

Q1 2025, according to the NY Fed. As a result, the unemployment gap between young grad-

uates and the general population is now the largest in ~35 years. Graduates are facing an

unemployment crisis.
